A/B test - Analyze the new website version

Using Python libraries such as Pandas, MatPlotLib, Seaborn, Numpy and SciPy in a Jupyter Notebook. Exploring generated revenues of two website variant, testing them in various different statistical techniques to be able to deploy the A/B test.

I'm very excited about this project, since I was studying this in university. It'll be very interesting to go over all my notes and migrate this knowledge from excel. This will be my first time to use SkiPy library.

The data¶

I was searching for a dataset where there are more than one samples to test hypothesis. Found this csv which contains raw data of the results of a new website lunch.

The business task is to do an A/B test and check if there is a significant increase in revenue between the two site variant.

As we always do, we will handle this dataset as it's ROCCC:

  • Reliable, Original and Cited: complete time series, which are accurate for the task and is non-bias. We will treat them as second-party datasets from a reliable organization.
  • Current and Comprehensive: we consider them as regularly refreshed datasets, which are appropriate and will enable us to answer the business questions.

Data has been downloaded and stored locally and uploaded into Google Drive as a back-up.

In the real world the data would be coming from a lot of source including various different BI tools (f.e. HubSpot, Google Optimize, Oracle Maxymiser). These tools, based on their own functionality, would automatically produce a similar dataset as their common "base" function. However, if we don't have such tools, we can always rely on Python.

Check if it's normal distribution¶

We need to check if it's a normal distribution to be able to choose the proper statistical technique for the test.

First, let's create a histogram to check by visualize method and see if we get the a bell shape.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(3, 3))
      plt.hist(df['REVENUE'], bins = 5)
Out[ ]:
(array([9.981e+03, 1.300e+01, 2.000e+00, 1.000e+00, 2.000e+00]),
       array([ 0.   , 11.726, 23.452, 35.178, 46.904, 58.63 ]),
       <BarContainer object of 5 artists>)

We can already assume from this histogram, that we are not dealing with a normal distribution.

For a formal statistical test, we can use the Shapiro-Wilk test. If the p-value of the test is greater than α = 0.05, then the data is assumed to be normally distributed. Nevertheless, p-value may not be accurate for N > 5000, so we need to reduce the df randomly.

In [ ]:
# Let's drop the 80% of our data, and use random_state to lock the results:
      randomdrop = df.sample(frac = 0.8, random_state = 200)
      df_saph = df.drop(randomdrop.index)
In [ ]:

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import shapiro 
      
      shapiro(df_saph['REVENUE'])
Out[ ]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.06637877225875854, pvalue=0.0)

From the output we can see that the test statistic is 0.066 and the corresponding p-value is 0.00. Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis of the Shapiro-Wilk test.

This means we have sufficient evidence to say that our df does not come from a normal distribution.

I'm afraid we are not at the best start, but let's check our data again and see if we can find a method to generate a normal distribution out of our dataset.¶

If we drop all of these 0 unit revenues, we'll get an exponential distribution.

One way we can address this issue is to transform the distribution of values (revenue) using one of the three transformations:

  • Log: transforms from y to log(y)
  • Square root: transforms from y to √y
  • Cube root: transforms from y to y^1/3

The following code creates side-by-side plots to help us choose the one that would give us the best bell-shape out of all the transformations.

In [ ]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=4)
      axs[0].hist(df2['REVENUE'], edgecolor='black')
      axs[1].hist(np.log(df2['REVENUE']), edgecolor='black')
      axs[2].hist(np.cbrt(df2['REVENUE']), edgecolor='black')
      axs[3].hist(np.sqrt(df2['REVENUE']), edgecolor='black')
      
      axs[0].set_title('Original Data')
      axs[1].set_title('Log')
      axs[2].set_title('Cube root')
      axs[3].set_title('Square root')

In my opinion the cube root would give us the best shape - however, since all the revenues are positive, I'd like to try out the Box-Cox method:

It looks like our revenue data finally have normal distribution, although Box-cox does not guarantee normality for the simple reason it never checks for it (but only the smallest standard deviation).

Therefore, we must make sure to check the transformed data.

A/B Testing (two-sample t-test)¶

Null hypothesis (H0): There is no significant difference in the revenue's median between the different site variants.

Alternative hypothesis (H1): There is a significant in difference in the revenue's median between the different site variants.

Significance level (α) = 0.05
We're assuming a 5% level of significance, which results a 95% confidence level.

To check the hypothesis I'm going to use the two-sample t-test. For this we need to make sure of the following two:

  • The data have normal distribution. If not, the randomly sampled dataset's distribution must be normally distributed.
  • The two site variable's variances must be equal.
In [ ]:
stat, p = shapiro(df_sample['REVENUE'])
      print('The test-statistic and p-value are the following:\nTest-statistic = %.3f , p-value = %.8f'%(stat,p))
      
The test-statistic and p-value are the following:
      Test-statistic = 0.956 , p-value = 0.00009261

As seen at the beginning, the H0 of this test is that the sample data is normally distributed. Unfortunately, after all of the effort with the transformations the Shapiro–Wilk test's p-value is much below the α = 0.05. That means the test tells us to reject the hypothesis as there is a statistical evidence that the data isn't normally distributed.

Most probably the reason behind it is that we removed the 0 unit revenues and it left us with a very small dataset. Obviously if the dataset is big enough, it increasignly getting closer to the normal distribution.

However, we checked the probplot already, and it seemd roughly on the best-fit line, we can check one last thing: the Q-Q plot.

In statistics, a Q–Q plot (quantile-quantile plot) is a probability plot for comparing two probability distributions by plotting their quantiles against each other. This plot provides a summary of whether the distributions of two variables are similar or not with respect to the locations.

In [ ]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
      
      fig = sm.qqplot(df_sample['REVENUE'], line='45')
      plt.show()

It's definetly not on the line, but maybe slightly similar..

I have read about the topic and it seems like that the t-test can be used on non-normal data as well. When there are more than ~25 observations per group and no extreme outliers, the t-test works well even for moderately skewed distributions of the outcome variable.

With this good news let's check the second t-test criteria, the equality of the two site variant's variance:

In [ ]:
# Group up sample data based on variant name
      variant = df_sample[df_sample['VARIANT_NAME']== 'variant']['REVENUE']
      control = df_sample[df_sample['VARIANT_NAME']== 'control']['REVENUE']
      
      # Set alpha
      alpha = 0.05
In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import levene
      
      # According to scipy.org, the Levene test checks the null hypothesis that all input samples are from populations with equal
      # variances. Levene’s test is an alternative to Bartlett’s test in the case where there are significant
      # deviations from normality.
      
      stat, p = levene(variant, control)
      
      print(stat, p)
      
      if p < alpha:
          print("Null hypothesis rejected. There is a significant discrepancy between the two site variant's variances")
      else:
          print("Null hypothesis not rejected. There is no a significant discrepancy between the two site variant's variances")
      
0.2496311128873615 0.6180719375539684
      Null hypothesis not rejected. There is no a significant discrepancy between the two site variant's variances

This means that the data passed our second criteria, so we can finally test the two-sample t-test!

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
      
      # This is a test of the null hypothesis that the average values of the two independent site variant are the same.
      
      
      # T-test for the means of two independent samples
      t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(variant, control)
      
      # Print the results
      print('test-statistic:', round(t_stat, 2))
      print('p-value:', p_val)
      
      if p_val < alpha:
          print("Null hypothesis rejected. There is no significant difference in the revenue's median between the different site variants.")
      else:
          print("Null hypothesis not rejected. There is a significant difference in the revenue's median between the different site variants.")
      
test-statistic: -1.33
      p-value: 0.18441761929883582
      Null hypothesis not rejected. There is a significant difference in the revenue's median between the different site variants.

As our A/B test result, we can conclude that there is a significant difference in the revenue between the control (original site) and the variant (new site), as their mean differences are significant and the p-values are less than 0.05. This means that at a 95% confidence level we can say that the new site variant has a significant difference in revenue. However, this test cannot tell us which site variant produced the bigger revenue.

The following pivot will answer this question:

Summary¶

  • The dataset have exponential distribution for the examined variable (revenue units).
  • We check the transformation options (log, square root and cube root)
  • Since the revenues are positive, we applied the Box-Cox transformation method
  • We got close to a normal distribution, but the Shapiro-Wilk test disproved it
  • Most probably the small sample data caused this disturbance
  • We went ahead and checked the two site variable's variances that they are equal.
  • At the end, we decided to do the two-sample t-test on our data

Conclusion¶

  • More than 98% of the site visits are not generating revenues.
  • The control site (new site) generated 7 more visits that resulted a revenue.
  • The A/B test results that there is a significant difference in the revenue between the control (original site) and the variant (new site).
  • This means that at a 95% confidence level we can say that the new site variant has a significant difference in revenue.
  • On average the variant (new site) generated more revenue.

My advise it to keep the new site while using BI tools to gather more qualitative and quantitative user insights. The goal would be to find triggers that results revenues, which would give us the path to deploy a more succesful website.
